[normal]TAKING ACTION WHEN A REGISTRANT’S FTP FALLS BELOW STANDARDS
[normal]Meeting the HCPC’s Burden of Proof – Evidence Given Based on Personal Interaction
[normal]The HCPC lay claim to 
[normal]robust governance arrangements, [bold]overall[bold] effective casework systems and efficient business processes[bold]. 
[normal]Allegations 
[normal]Allegations were revised seven months 
[normal]AFTER
[normal] ICP agreement and 
[normal]AFTER ALL
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]evidence had been gathered from both sides.  These amended allegations were accepted by a CCC on the day of a hearing. This process was considered to be ‘fair’ to better reflect the HCPC’s burden of proof.  The HCPC considers a CCC to have an 
[normal]inherent power[bold] to undertake this process.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Out of 223 final FTP hearings between 1
[normal]st
[normal] November 2012 and 30
[normal]th
[normal] June 2013 
[normal]103 FTP cases had amendments made to their allegations[bold].
[normal]Civil Rules of Evidence – HCPC’s Reliance on Hearsay Evidence
[normal]The HCPC’s burden of proof relied purely upon tenuous witness ‘hearsay’ evidence which was ‘peppered’ with inconsistencies that did not match with documentary evidence.  The HCPC withheld and did not disclose evidence from senior NHS management that identified an inappropriate workplace culture to be in existence and provided no cogent reasons for the failure to call such a critical witness.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Information taken from Professor Berwick’s report a Promise to Learn – A Commitment to Act
[normal]Information taken from Kingsley 
[normal]Napley
[normal] Solicitors’ Legal Updates – Autumn 2011
[normal]Documentary Evidence Handling
[normal]The HCPC omitted from the investigation process and failed to disclose to the proceedings critical, exculpatory documentary evidence in the form of 
[normal]Patient Care Records[bold],  claiming the disclosure of this evidence to be ‘desirable’ but not ‘essential’ to fulfill their burden of proof.  A 
[normal]dishonest[bold] written statement made by the HCPC exists that states this evidence is no longer available when it is in fact in their possession.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Kinglsey
[normal] 
[normal]Napley
[normal] Solicitors – Legal Updates – Autumn 2011 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]identified “an increase in administrative errors on the part of the HCPC, which included 
[normal]evidence missing from bundles, incorrect information given to panels[bold] and not enough notice being given to a registrant.”
