[normal]HCPC Audit Conducted by Professional Standards Authority - September 2013
[normal]We identified “
[normal]weaknesses or areas for improvement[bold] in 53 of the cases, including 25 cases where we had 
[normal]concerns about the HCPC’s decision making[bold] and six cases where we 
[normal]considered there were potential implications[bold] for public protection and/or 
[normal]maintaining public confidence in the profession or its system of regulation[bold].
[normal] 
[normal]Failing to gather sufficient information, which resulted in decision makers taking decisions without the benefit of all potentially relevant evidence[bold] in 15 cases.
[normal]
[normal] 
[normal]Credibility of decisions[bold] 
[normal]
[normal] 
[normal]Weaknesses in customer care[bold]
[normal] 
[normal]Inadequate record keeping[bold] 
[normal] “Of the 100 cases audited, we identified 31 cases in which we had 
[normal]concerns around risk assessments and [bold]compliance with the HCPC’s operational guidance[bold].[bold] 
[normal]More specifically, we found 27 cases (including cases closed by HCPC staff and following an ICP decision) where risk assessments had not been completed at all required stages in the process.
[normal]Conducting a robust risk assessment on receipt of a new complaint and updating that risk assessment in light of new information is an important part of public protection within a risk-based regulatory approach. 
[normal]Unless the regulator has conducted a proper evaluation of risk, it is difficult to make sound [bold]judgements[bold] [bold]about whether any regulatory action is necessary,”
[normal]We recommend that the HCPC reviews our findings in these cases and considers whether improvements can be made to its processes and procedures to [bold]minimise[bold] the risk of any of the issues highlighted above reoccurring in the future.[bold]In response to this external audit, the HCPC published:
[normal]“Overall[bold] the PSA found that “the HCPC continues to operate effective systems and processes in all areas of its 
[normal]initial
[normal] stages of the FTP process”.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Taking into account the 
[normal]overall [bold]failures to casework systems and business processes as identified above:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A PROMISE TO LEARN, A COMMITMENT TO ACT AND A DUTY OF CANDOUR, DISCLOSURE AND OPENNESS
[normal]225 final hearings came before a conduct and competence committee. 14 registrants had conditions of practice imposed, 40 had a caution imposed, 44 were struck off and 61 were suspended.
[normal]292 registrants made a self-referral of disclosure to the HCPC.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]NHS staff are not to blame, in the vast majority of cases it is the systems, procedures, conditions, environment and constraints that they face that lead to patient safety problems.  [bold]Well intentioned people who make errors or are involved in systems that have failed around them need to be supported, not punished.[bold]  [bold]Genuine errors are not misconduct and do not warrant punishment[bold]?[bold]&#xa0;
